05913nam a22008055i 9781501734298DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191995nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017342987 a10.7591/97815017342982doi  a(DE-B1597)534203  a(OCoLC)1121056679  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0110002bisacsh00aInternational Organizations and Ethnic Conflict /ced. by Shibley Z. Telhami, Milton J. Esman. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tA Note to the Reader -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. The Role of International Organizations in the Post-Cold-War Era -- t1. A Survey of Interventions -- t2. The Past, the Present, and the Future Prospects -- t3. Anomie, System Reform, and Challenges to the UN System -- tPART II. The Case of Lebanon -- t4. The Case of Nineteenth- Century Lebanon -- t5. The Domestic Context and Perspectives in Lebanon -- t6. How Peace Keeping Becomes Intervention: Lessons from the Lebanese Experience -- tPART III. The Case of Yugoslavia -- t7. Historical Roots of the Yugoslav Conflict -- t8. Redrawing Borders in a Period of Systemic Transition -- t9. The International Community and the Yugoslav Crisis -- tPART IV. Conclusion -- t10. An Outline of a Comparison Between Yugoslavia and Lebanon -- t11. Changing Roles -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom Rwanda to Somalia to the former Yugoslavia, one feature of the post-Cold War world has become dreadfully clear. Ethnic conflicts are escalating, and with them demands for international intervention. But legally most ethnic conflicts are "internal" matters. How are international organizations, their resources stretched woefully thin, to know when intervention is appropriate or possible? This volume addresses the changing nature of relations between war-torn multiethnic states and international organizations, particularly the United Nations and its agencies.Are the established norms that limit intervention in ethnic conflicts adequate to contemporary conditions? Can international organizations meet the increasing demand? If not, what are the consequences of the disparities between established norms, current capabilities, and expanding expectations—and how might these disparities be narrowed? The contributors explore the desirability and potential effectiveness of international interventions in ethnic conflicts. Detailed studies of two specific cases of severe and violent tensions, in Lebanon and Yugoslavia, complement the general discussion with particular insights into the risks and exigencies of international attempts to manage ethnic civil war.A deeply thoughtful overview of one of the most pressing and perplexing issues confronting the world today, this volume clarifies the changing role of international organizations in an increasingly fragmented world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aEthnic Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aBurg, Steven L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonnelly, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsman, Milton J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsman, Milton J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGagnon, V. P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHopkins, Raymond F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudson, Michael C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l